<PageLayout
  title="Act II: Building an Engineer"
  description="Hanson: an unexpected move to Ohio, sales quoting software across five regions, and years on the road with the team. Meisel: leaving Hanson behind for a small software company in Carrollton. GimmalSoft is still being written."
>
  <BackLink href="/career">Back to My Career</BackLink>

  <header class="mb-8">
    <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-300 mb-1">
      Act II
    </p>
    <h1 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight text-neutral-900 dark:text-neutral-100">
      Building an Engineer
    </h1>
  </header>

  <ChapterTOC sections={sections} class="mb-10" />

  <div
    class="prose prose-neutral dark:prose-invert max-w-none prose-a:text-brand-600 dark:prose-a:text-brand-300 prose-code:font-mono prose-code:before:content-none prose-code:after:content-none"
  >
    <h2 id="hanson">Hanson</h2>

    <h3 id="an-unexpected-offer">An Unexpected Offer</h3>

    <p>
      While working on a particularly difficult issue with Magic Help Desk's
      Change Management module, I received an email from Kevin, the Region
      Finance Manager for the Northeast Area. Somehow, my name had come up as
      a possible candidate for a database administrator position in his
      region, and he wanted to know if I was interested.
    </p>

    <p>
      I had absolutely no idea what that entailed, but the pay increase was
      worth investigating, especially since I was only 25 at the time.
    </p>

    <p>
      Kevin's boss was Bob, the president of the Northeast Region, so I knew
      the opportunity had some real clout behind it. After a quick phone
      interview where Kevin learned a little about me and introduced me to
      the position, he invited me to fly to Columbus for a face-to-face
      interview with him and Bob.
    </p>

    <p>
      I had never been to Ohio before. I remember liking the Columbus airport
      and thinking downtown looked quite nice, at least the parts I saw. The
      interview and dinner went well, and they offered me the position. Of
      course, they understood that I needed to discuss it with my wife.
    </p>

    <p>
      We realized this would mean uprooting our lives and leaving the state
      we had called home since we were young kids. We had only been married
      a short while, though, so it didn't seem like as big of a deal as it
      would today.
    </p>

    <p>We decided to give it a shot.</p>

    <h3 id="a-week-in-ohio">A Week in Ohio</h3>

    <p>
      We contacted a realtor, prepared our house as best we could, and put it
      on the market. Hanson worked with a relocation service that flew us to
      Columbus for a week, giving us a chance to learn the area and find
      somewhere to live.
    </p>

    <p>
      We explored towns like Hilliard, Dublin, Westerville, and Pickerington.
      We took a quick drive through parts of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ohio_State_University" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">The Ohio State University</a> and
      spent time getting familiar with a city that might soon become our
      home.
    </p>

    <p>But we had a hankerin' for some Chicago pizza.</p>

    <p>
      So we hopped in the car, called our cousins in Oak Park, Illinois, and
      asked if they wanted to grab some <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gino%27s_East" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Gino's East</a>. We drove through Fort
      Wayne, Valparaiso, and Gary until we reached Chicago and encountered
      toll roads we were absolutely not prepared for. We ate great pizza,
      shared plenty of laughs, and enjoyed time with our family. We stayed in
      a hotel overnight, then drove back the next day through Indianapolis
      while watching our clocks do some fun things as we crossed back and
      forth between time zones.
    </p>

    <p>
      By the time we returned to Texas, we thought we had found an apartment
      complex in Pickerington where we would like to live.
    </p>

    <p>Now we just needed our house to sell.</p>

    <h3 id="building-a-better-quote">Building a Better Quote</h3>

    <p>
      Around this time, I started working with the new team. We were
      designing sales quoting software that would help the sales team
      quickly build complex quotes for our pipe and precast business. The
      project represented five territories across the United States and Canada:
      Northeast, Northwest, Southeast, South Central, and Southwest.
    </p>

    <p>
      My job was to keep the Northeast Region's price sheet up to date in the
      backend database. How much did twelve-inch pipe of a certain thickness
      cost per lineal foot? That was the kind of question the software
      needed to answer.
    </p>

    <p>
      The Canadian regions introduced another layer of complexity. We knew
      that one inch equaled 25.4 millimeters, but that didn't mean a
      twelve-inch pipe was called a 304.8-millimeter pipe. It was called a
      300-millimeter pipe. Some conversions were rounded according to the
      terminology used by the industry, while others needed to remain
      precise. We couldn't simply multiply everything by 25.4 and assume the
      answer would make sense to the people using the software.
    </p>

    <p>
      Then there was currency. Prices had to account for the differences
      between U.S. and Canadian dollars, adding one more set of rules to a
      system that was already full of regional products, measurements,
      pricing, and business logic.
    </p>

    <p>
      The project was spearheaded primarily by Milt from Tampa and Shelley,
      our project manager from Cincom Systems. We had a huge, amazing team,
      with a core group consisting of Glenn, Joel, Carissa, AD, Dan from
      Saratoga Systems, Brian from Cincom, and me. We also coordinated with
      numerous people throughout the different regions, gathering their
      input and learning how each part of the business operated.
    </p>

    <p>
      The software itself was a strange hodgepodge of technologies and
      integrations. We used <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/.NET_Framework" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">.NET</a> alongside Cincom's Socrates software, a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Delphi_(software)" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Delphi</a>-based
      dynamic configurator that generated the user interface. Saratoga
      Systems' iAvenue served as our local database, with <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Component_Object_Model" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">COM</a> integrations
      tying pieces of the system together.
    </p>

    <p>
      The software would periodically "call home," synchronizing each local
      database with a global database. I was responsible for maintaining the
      Northeast Region's pricing data in that global system.
    </p>

    <p>
      When the project began, we traveled to different locations so the team
      could work together, plan, get up to speed, and make forward progress.
      We often gathered in Hanson's Irving or Las Colinas offices, at
      Cincom's office in Cincinnati, or at the Hanson office in Green Cove
      Springs, Florida.
    </p>

    <p>
      As we completed each region, we held a huge rollout meeting with the
      sales team and company executives. There was wining and dining, and I
      finally had the opportunity to meet many of the people I had
      previously known only as voices on the other end of a help desk call.
    </p>

    <p>It felt like we were on top of the world.</p>

    <h3 id="becoming-a-developer">Becoming a Developer</h3>

    <p>
      During one of those rollout meetings, I remember sitting in a hotel hallway
      with Brian and Shelley. I was curious, so I started asking questions
      about the code and how all the different pieces worked together.
      Brian took the time to show me, and it didn't take long for him to
      realize that the code wasn't foreign to me.
    </p>

    <p>
      Brian began working his way up the chain, asking whether I could
      become one of the developers on the project.
    </p>

    <p>There was no hesitation. The executives approved the change.</p>

    <p>
      Instead of entering data, I was now learning how Socrates and iAvenue
      worked and how we used .NET as the harness that held everything
      together. Brian became my development partner, while Milt and Shelley
      continued leading the team.
    </p>

    <p>The four of us worked like a family: We laughed. We fought. We ate.</p>

    <p>And we traveled almost every single week.</p>

    <h3 id="life-on-the-road">Life on the Road</h3>

    <p>
      We met in cities across the United States and Canada: Tampa,
      Cincinnati, St. Augustine, Miami, Pittsburgh, Portland, Sacramento,
      Toronto, Windsor, and plenty of places in between. I've been blessed
      with fond memories from every one of them.
    </p>

    <p>
      We spent a lot of time in Tampa, hanging out at Milt's house, visiting
      his favorite places, and getting to know his grown kids.
    </p>

    <p>
      When we worked in Cincinnati, I would often fly into Dayton and drive
      south to West Chester, while Milt would fly into Cincinnati. We spent
      long hours in hotel lobbies slinging code, then relaxed over dinner and wine at
      Jag's Steak &amp; Seafood. Before flying home, I would sometimes stay
      overnight in Dayton and catch a movie by myself. As much as I enjoyed
      traveling with the team, I also enjoyed those quiet evenings and the
      rare opportunity to spend a little time alone.
    </p>

    <p>
      In St. Augustine, we sat on the beach and explored the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Castillo_de_San_Marcos" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Castillo de
      San Marcos</a> and the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St._Augustine_Lighthouse" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">St. Augustine Lighthouse</a>. From the windows of the
      Miami Marriott Biscayne Bay, we watched as a Category 1 hurricane moved
      through the city.
    </p>

    <p>
      Toronto brought a different set of memories. I remember leaving the
      airport and having to remind myself that the speed limit was measured
      in kilometers per hour rather than miles per hour as I drove toward
      Cambridge. I tried <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poutine" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">poutine</a>, and we drove along the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Queen_Elizabeth_Way" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Queen Elizabeth
      Way</a> to see <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Niagara_Falls" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Niagara Falls</a>. Even the ordinary parts of those trips,
      like navigating unfamiliar roads in a rental car, felt like an
      adventure.
    </p>

    <p>
      Milt took us to his hometown of Pittsburgh and showed us pieces of his
      life. I remember flying into the airport, driving through the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fort_Pitt_Tunnel" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fort
      Pitt Tunnel</a>, and emerging to one of the most stunning views of a city
      imaginable.
    </p>

    <p>That view is burned into my brain.</p>

    <p>
      Milt took us to a Pirates game at <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PNC_Park" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">PNC Park</a>, and we ate at the original <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Primanti_Bros." target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Primanti
      Bros</a>. Those trips hold some of the most iconic memories of my life,
      and they all happened within a relatively short period. I have enough
      stories to fill an entire chapter.
    </p>

    <p>
      But the places weren't what made those years special. It was the
      people I experienced them with. The team had become my family, and
      that is something I would never trade.
    </p>

    <h3 id="the-move-that-never-happened">The Move That Never Happened</h3>

    <p>
      As the project progressed, it became clear that our house wasn't going
      to sell. The housing bubble was about to burst. Our home's value had
      fallen, and no one seemed interested in buying in our area.
    </p>

    <p>
      Joan was the president of the Southeast Region, based in Green Cove
      Springs, Florida. She commanded a room when she entered, but never in
      an overpowering way. You instinctively respected her, and you knew she
      would return that respect with boldness and kindness at the same time.
      You could be a little scared of her and admire her at once.
    </p>

    <p>
      One day, Joan called and asked whether we had received any offers on
      our house. When I dejectedly told her it had been crickets, she asked
      a different question.
    </p>

    <p>"Do you even want to move?"</p>

    <p>"I really don't," I admitted. "I love Texas."</p>

    <p>"Then you don't have to move. Just continue working remotely like you have been."</p>

    <p>
      She didn't say it as a suggestion. She didn't say she would look into
      it or see what she could do. It was a simple declaration, delivered
      with enough authority that there was no doubt left in the
      conversation.
    </p>

    <p>It was as good as done.</p>

    <p>Joan wasn't even my boss.</p>

    <p>
      She made calls to Kevin and Bob, and that was the end of it. She even
      arranged for me to transfer from Kevin's team to work for AD. There
      were no hard feelings. By that point, I was doing far more development
      work than data entry anyway.
    </p>

    <p>We could stay home.</p>

    <h3 id="one-more-opportunity">One More Opportunity</h3>

    <p>
      Eventually, the travel began to wind down, and we spent more time
      working from the Las Colinas office. One day, I decided to look on <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Craigslist" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Craigslist</a> to
      see whether there were any part-time development jobs available.
    </p>

    <p>
      I had no intention of leaving Hanson. I truly enjoyed working there. I
      simply wanted more opportunities to write software and continue
      learning.
    </p>

    <p>
      I found a listing for part-time work with Meisel, a company in
      Carrollton, Texas. Like most of my job interviews up to that point,
      the process was surprisingly simple. Brad and George asked about my
      experience but didn't require a coding exercise or put me through a
      complicated technical interview.
    </p>

    <p>They took a gamble on me, just as Rob and Kevin had before them.</p>

    <p>
      The tasks Brad gave me weren't overly complicated, but I still had
      plenty to learn. I didn't know <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Windows_Forms" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">WinForms</a> particularly well. I was still
      a junior developer. But with every assignment, I did the best work I
      could and tried to meet the standards Brad and George expected.
    </p>

    <p>That continued for nine months.</p>

    <p>Then they made me an offer.</p>

    <p>"Kyle, we'd like you to come work for Meisel full-time."</p>

    <h2 id="meisel">Meisel</h2>

    <h3 id="the-next-opportunity">The Next Opportunity</h3>

    <p>Leaving Hanson wasn't easy.</p>

    <p>
      What started as a help desk job had turned into so much more. Somewhere
      between airports, hotel lobbies, rollout meetings, late nights writing
      code, and countless meals together, my coworkers had become family.
    </p>

    <p>Milt especially.</p>

    <p>
      He insisted I walked like Big Bird from <em>Sesame Street</em>, and
      somehow the nickname stuck. We logged thousands of miles together,
      explored cities all over North America, argued over software,
      discovered new restaurants, and laughed until our sides hurt. Years
      later, I found the email he sent after I left Hanson. One line stood
      out above the rest:
    </p>

    <blockquote>
      <p>I stopped thinking about you as a business co-worker long ago.</p>
    </blockquote>

    <p>
      He's absolutely right. It was evident to us and everyone around that
      we were family.
    </p>

    <p>
      The funny thing is that I never set out to leave Hanson in the first
      place. Looking for a part-time development job wasn't an exit strategy.
      I genuinely enjoyed working there. I simply wanted to keep learning.
      Brad and George gave me that opportunity, and for nine months I spent
      my evenings writing software for Meisel while continuing my full-time
      job at Hanson.
    </p>

    <p>Then they made me an offer.</p>

    <p>
      Leaving meant saying goodbye to people who had shaped me, encouraged
      me, challenged me, and become lifelong friends. It wasn't an easy
      decision, but I knew it was the right one.
    </p>

    <p>
      And again, without even realizing it, I found myself standing at
      another unexpected fork. This one didn't lead to another airport or another city.
      It led to a small printing company tucked away near the corner of
      Valwood Parkway and Luna Road in Carrollton.
    </p>

    <h3 id="a-place-called-meisel">A Place Called Meisel</h3>

    <p>
      The building wasn't particularly impressive from the outside, but I
      can still picture it almost perfectly.
    </p>

    <p>
      Downstairs were the account representatives, our tiny two-person IT
      department, the server room, the art department, and a warehouse full
      of equipment that fascinated me from the day I walked in. Upstairs sat
      sales, accounting, George's office, Brad's office, and my little corner
      of the development team. My cubicle was part of a group of four just
      outside George's office, while Brad occupied the office next door.
    </p>

    <p>George's door was almost always open.</p>

    <p>
      He wasn't my direct manager. Brad filled that role. George was my
      boss's boss, the company president, our product owner, and, more often
      than not, our QA department. For someone carrying that many
      responsibilities, he was remarkably approachable. If you needed to ask
      a question, bounce around an idea, or admit you were stuck, you simply
      walked into his office.
    </p>

    <p>
      George was from Connecticut, loved golf, and always seemed to wear a
      smile. I honestly don't remember ever seeing him lose his temper. He
      was calm without being passive, decisive without being intimidating,
      and deeply knowledgeable about the printing business. Every feature we
      discussed, every workflow we designed, and every decision we made was
      rooted in his understanding of how the company actually operated.
    </p>

    <p>
      We didn't run Scrum. There were no daily standups or sprint
      retrospectives. SharePoint loosely tracked our work, but most of our
      planning happened in the meeting room with a projector, a keyboard, and
      the three of us talking through whatever problem sat in front of us.
    </p>

    <p>
      George understood the business better than anyone I'd ever met. Brad
      taught me how to build software that served it. I found myself
      learning from both of them every single day.
    </p>

    <p>
      Brad and I quickly settled into a rhythm that would define my years at
      Meisel.
    </p>

    <p>
      Most days I'd pull up the straight-backed visitor chair in his office
      while he sat behind his desk. We'd talk about whatever we were working
      on, brainstorm solutions, or chase down bugs that had somehow escaped
      us. Just as often, we'd stop talking about software altogether.
    </p>

    <p>
      We talked about marching band a lot. I played trumpet. Brad played
      trombone and had marched with the University of Texas. It didn't take
      long for us to discover we spoke the same language. He loved airplanes
      and was always checking FlightAware to see what was flying overhead.
      He also rode recumbent bicycles. His dad worked for a company that
      manufactured industrial trackballs, and Brad used one every day
      instead of a mouse.
    </p>

    <p>He swore it was more ergonomic. <em>I couldn't stand the thing.</em></p>

    <p>
      Lunch became just as much a part of our routine as Visual Studio. We'd
      usually head toward the old Hanson stomping grounds around I-635 and
      MacArthur. Taco Bueno, Chipotle, Whataburger, Steak 'n Shake. Sometimes
      we'd run a quick errand while we were out, but we tried to be
      respectful of the flexibility George gave us. Nobody was watching the
      clock. That trust made us want to honor it.
    </p>

    <p>
      Over time, Brad stopped feeling like my manager and started feeling
      like my brother.
    </p>

    <p>
      Almost every day we worked side by side as coworkers and friends. Once
      or twice a year we'd have to switch gears and pretend to be boss and
      employee for a performance review. It always felt awkward because it
      wasn't really who we were the other 363 days of the year.
    </p>

    <p>Life happened in that office.</p>

    <p>
      I walked with Brad through his divorce and saw firsthand how difficult
      that season was for his family. Later, I celebrated with him as he
      married Jessica, and I'm grateful to see them still happily together
      today.
    </p>

    <p>When I think about Meisel, I don't immediately think about software.</p>

    <p>I think about that straight-backed chair in Brad's office.</p>

    <p>
      That's where I learned some of the most important lessons of my
      career, and very few of them had anything to do with writing code.
    </p>

    <h3 id="following-my-curiosity">Following My Curiosity</h3>

    <p>
      Most of my day revolved around FocalPoint, Meisel's custom <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Enterprise_resource_planning" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ERP</a> system.
    </p>

    <p>
      It wasn't something you could buy off the shelf. It was software built
      specifically for Meisel, by Meisel, shaped by years of experience in
      the printing industry and constantly evolving alongside the business.
      It existed for one reason: to help Meisel run its business. Every new
      feature solved a real problem for someone upstairs, downstairs, or in
      the warehouse.
    </p>

    <p>
      The application itself was written in <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Visual_Basic_.NET" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">VB.NET</a> on <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/.NET_Framework" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">.NET Framework</a> 3.5, and we
      spent our days inside Visual Studio 2008. Brad maintained an older ORM
      called DeKlarit that only worked in Visual Studio 2005, generating our
      DataSets, DataTables, and TableAdapters. We used Redgate to migrate
      database schema changes between environments, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ClickOnce" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ClickOnce</a> deployed
      updates to everyone's computer, and Infragistics supplied most of our
      user interface controls.
    </p>

    <p>I had a love-hate relationship with the Infragistics UltraGrid.</p>

    <p>
      It was incredibly powerful, but it could also be incredibly slow if
      you weren't careful. George had developed a very specific style for
      how he wanted grids to behave. Required fields were highlighted in a
      soft yellow. Certain data types would have specified ways to be
      displayed. Layouts stayed consistent from screen to screen. Users
      shouldn't have to relearn the software every time they opened another
      window. At the time, I simply thought, "This is how George likes it."
      Over the years, I've come to appreciate how much thought he had put
      into making software comfortable for the people who spent all day
      using it.
    </p>

    <p>
      The most detailed form in the application centered around an Order. One of
      its tabs displayed every Order Item, and every one of those items was
      represented by a user control called <code>ucOrderItem</code>. Each
      control contained several Infragistics controls of its own, including
      another UltraGrid. It worked well enough, but once an order became
      large, that tab took forever to load. If somebody handed me that code
      today, I'd love another shot at it.
    </p>

    <p>
      As much as I enjoyed writing software, I don't think I ever viewed my
      job as just sitting in a cubicle writing code.
    </p>

    <p>I loved wandering downstairs. The warehouse fascinated me.</p>

    <p>
      Customers would send us Adobe Illustrator files, Photoshop documents,
      EPS artwork, and PDFs. Those files first landed with the art
      department, where they cleaned everything up and made sure it was
      ready for production. From there, the warehouse took over. Watching an
      Illustrator file become a giant printed display was just plain cool.
      Huge printers covered sheets of media that seemed impossibly large.
      Some jobs were mounted to foam board. Others were laminated, trimmed,
      or assembled into displays that would eventually end up in stores all
      over the country.
    </p>

    <p>Then someone had to figure out how to package all of it.</p>

    <p>That part fascinated me just as much.</p>

    <p>
      It wasn't enough to print something that looked great. It had to
      survive forklifts, conveyor belts, trucks, delivery drivers, and
      everything else between Carrollton and the customer. I worked closely
      with Daniel, who led the shipping and packaging department, and the
      more time I spent with him, the more I realized how many problems
      existed that software could actually help solve.
    </p>

    <p>One of the biggest projects we worked on together was shipping.</p>

    <p>
      FocalPoint already managed orders, but we built one of the largest
      grids in the application to organize shipments and keep track of every
      FedEx and UPS tracking number. We integrated with their <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SOAP" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">SOAP</a> web
      services so employees could see shipment status without bouncing
      between different websites. It wasn't glamorous work, but it solved
      real problems for the people using it every day, and those were always
      my favorite kinds of projects.
    </p>

    <p>
      Around that same time, Meisel expanded into the suite next door and
      converted most of it into additional warehouse space. Suddenly
      inventory became a much bigger challenge, which led us to another
      project I thoroughly enjoyed.
    </p>

    <p>
      We built an inventory management system around Motorola MC9090G
      handheld scanners running the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/.NET_Compact_Framework" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">.NET Compact Framework</a>.
    </p>

    <p>
      I had never written software for a handheld device before, so that
      alone was exciting. But just like everything else at Meisel, the
      project quickly became about much more than writing code.
    </p>

    <div class="my-6 space-y-1 border-l-2 border-neutral-300 dark:border-neutral-700 pl-4 italic">
      <p class="my-1">Where should the wireless access points go?</p>
      <p class="my-1">Would the scanners keep a reliable connection everywhere in the warehouse?</p>
      <p class="my-1">Were there dead spots?</p>
      <p class="my-1">How much overlap between access points was enough?</p>
    </div>

    <p>
      None of those questions had anything to do with VB.NET, but I loved
      learning about them anyway.
    </p>

    <p>Then there were the labels.</p>

    <p>
      We used Zebra thermal printers throughout the warehouse, so I found
      myself learning Zebra Programming Language, Eltron Programming
      Language, and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Code_39" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Code 39</a> barcodes so we could generate labels for
      inventory and shipping. If you had told the twenty-year-old version of
      me that I'd someday be writing software for handheld barcode scanners
      while worrying about Wi-Fi coverage and printer languages, I never
      would have believed you.
    </p>

    <p>
      That's one of the things I loved most about Meisel. There were no
      walls between departments.
    </p>

    <p>If I wanted to spend time downstairs with Daniel, nobody questioned it.</p>

    <p>
      If I wanted to hang around the server room with Butch and Xander, the
      door was always open. They never treated infrastructure as some secret
      club that developers weren't allowed to touch. They were always
      willing to teach us something new, and just as willing to hear our
      ideas if we thought we could help. I learned a tremendous amount
      simply by spending time with people who enjoyed what they did.
    </p>

    <h3 id="investing-in-people">Investing in People</h3>

    <p>
      At some point, Brad and I came up with a crazy idea. What if Meisel
      sent us to DevConnections in Las Vegas? We knew Meisel didn't have any
      type of real training budget, so we never expected George to say yes.
      Somehow, he did. In April 2010, Brad and I headed to Las Vegas to
      learn about .NET Framework 4.0, Visual Studio 2010, and everything
      Microsoft had coming next.
    </p>

    <p>
      We stayed at Mandalay Bay and spent our days bouncing between sessions
      before wandering the Strip at night. We walked through Caesars
      Palace, admired stores we couldn't afford to shop in, and ate an
      incredible buffet at Paris under what looked like a painted cerulean
      sky. It was one of those trips where you spent all day learning and
      all evening talking about what you had learned.
    </p>

    <p>
      I remember <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bob_Muglia" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Bob Muglia</a> delivering one of the keynote
      presentations. At the time he was leading Microsoft's Server and Tools
      Business, though I don't think I appreciated just how influential he
      was. I was simply excited to hear directly from the people building
      the platform we spent every day using.
    </p>

    <p>One session in particular has stayed with me.</p>

    <p>
      Stephen Toub gave a presentation on the new concurrency features
      coming to .NET 4. At the time, I had no idea who he was. I just
      remember sitting there thinking, "This guy is brilliant."
    </p>

    <p>
      As the years went by, I started seeing his name everywhere. Blog
      posts. Answers on Stack Overflow. Deep dives into the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallel_Extensions" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Task Parallel
      Library</a> and asynchronous programming. Whenever Stephen Toub wrote
      something, I knew it was worth reading. It eventually dawned on me
      that I'd unknowingly spent an afternoon learning from someone who
      would become one of my most trusted sources on .NET concurrency.
    </p>

    <p>
      As soon as Brad and I got back to the office, we upgraded FocalPoint
      to Visual Studio 2010 and .NET Framework 4. We didn't spend weeks
      planning the migration. We were excited, so we did it. The
      improvements were noticeable almost immediately, and one of the first
      places we put the new concurrency features to work was our shipment
      tracking updates. Instead of refreshing tracking numbers one request
      at a time, we used <code>Parallel.ForEach</code> to process multiple
      requests concurrently. It wasn't the kind of feature customers would
      ever notice, but we noticed it, and so did the people in the warehouse
      who depended on that information every day.
    </p>

    <h3 id="more-than-coworkers">More Than Coworkers</h3>

    <p>
      Around this time, our little development team also grew when Clayton
      joined us. Clayton was one of those people who always seemed to be
      building or fixing something. He was one of the biggest DIYers I've
      ever met. Whether it was working on cars, building something around
      the house, or tinkering with a new idea, he was always learning and
      figuring out how things worked.
    </p>

    <p>
      What made him even more interesting was that he hadn't taken the
      typical path into software. He had majored in Psychology simply
      because he wanted to study something completely different. That same
      curiosity seemed to carry over into everything he did, and I think it
      was one of the things that made him such a great developer.
    </p>

    <p>
      Before long, Brad, Clayton, and I had settled into our own routine of
      regular lunches at Tokyo Teriyaki. We all just called it "Tokyo T,"
      and I don't think I ever ordered anything besides the number one with
      no slaw, extra rice, and extra protein.
    </p>

    <p>
      Those lunches became one of my favorite parts of the week. We'd just
      talk like three guys who had been friends for a lifetime. Years after
      we had all left Meisel, we'd still find ourselves back at Tokyo T
      every now and then, picking up right where we left off.
    </p>

    <p>
      Unfortunately, business slowed, and Meisel eventually had to make the
      difficult decision to reduce its workforce. Clayton was one of the
      people affected, and it was hard to see him go. Losing a coworker is
      never easy, but it was especially difficult because by that point he
      had become a good friend.
    </p>

    <p>
      Thankfully, losing the job didn't mean losing the friendship. We
      stayed in touch, and over the years Clayton became one of those people
      I no longer think of as a former coworker. He's one of my closest
      friends.
    </p>

    <p>
      By this point, FocalPoint still consumed most of my time, but it
      wasn't the only product we were building.
    </p>

    <p>
      One of our products, ReadyLink, allowed <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Army_%26_Air_Force_Exchange_Service" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">AAFES</a> stores to order custom
      marketing materials directly from us. Around the same time, I was
      given the opportunity to build something entirely my own.
    </p>

    <p>
      Using <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ASP.NET_MVC" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ASP.NET MVC</a>, I built a web application that allowed customers
      to upload enormous PDF, AI, and EPS files directly to Meisel. Some of
      those files were larger than <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_Information_Services" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IIS</a> wanted to accept, so handling them
      took a little creativity. Once the upload finished, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ImageMagick" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ImageMagick</a> generated
      thumbnails of the artwork, the files were stored on our
      internal servers, and email notifications were automatically sent to
      both the account representatives and the art department so everyone
      knew new work had arrived.
    </p>

    <p>As a junior developer, I thought that was pretty stinking cool.</p>

    <p>
      Then one day, out of the blue, I received a call from an old college
      buddy.
    </p>

    <p>"Kyle."</p>

    <p>"It's Damon."</p>

    <h2 id="gimmal">GimmalSoft</h2>

    <h3 id="an-overnight-visit">An Overnight Visit</h3>

    <p>
      When I was a junior in high school, I was completely prepared to attend
      Texas Tech in Lubbock. My family and I had gone to visit, tour the
      campus, and even check out the honors dorm where I would be living. I
      was going to march in the "<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goin%27_Band_from_Raiderland" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Goin' Band from Raiderland</a>," and I was
      excited.
    </p>

    <p>However, God seemed to have another plan.</p>

    <p>
      As it got closer to the summer before my senior year, things just
      didn't quite fit as well. I honestly don't remember the exact reason I
      started looking at <a href="https://www.utdallas.edu" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">The University of Texas at Dallas</a> instead, but I
      did. UTD was only about twenty minutes from home, and a friend I'd
      known since middle school, Kenny, had decided to go there too. During
      the summer before our senior year, we signed up for one of UTD's
      overnight preview weekends.
    </p>

    <p>
      The only thing I really remember about that visit was staying with our
      student hosts in their on-campus apartment. That weekend we met TK and
      Amanda, along with their boyfriends, Damon and Nick. Most of them had
      actually been friends since high school, and they were all only about
      a year older than us. (Spoiler alert: Damon and TK are still married,
      and so are Nick and Amanda.)
    </p>

    <p>
      It wasn't surprising, then, that once we became freshmen at UTD, I
      became close friends with Damon, Nick, Tim, Matt, Ted, and the rest of
      the group. We spent a lot of time together playing <em>Super Smash
      Bros.</em>, making trips to Herrera's for Tex-Mex, throwing frisbees
      for Ultimate, learning to play guitar, and growing in our faith
      together. Tim was the one who taught me how to throw a frisbee well
      enough to actually play Ultimate. Nick had the unbelievable ability to
      beat everyone at <em>Super Smash Bros.</em> using only his feet. I'm
      serious.
    </p>

    <p>
      Kenny was my freshman roommate, but Matt was my roommate sophomore
      year. Matt is the reason I play guitar today. That was also the
      apartment I was living in while I worked at EarthLink.
    </p>

    <p>Damon also happened to be a great programmer, even back then.</p>

    <p>
      I remember taking a Visual Basic class where we were building Windows
      Forms applications. I hadn't seen WinForms in high school, and one of
      my homework assignments had me completely stuck. After pulling my hair
      out for a while, I finally called Damon.
    </p>

    <p>
      He didn't immediately know the answer either, but he patiently worked
      through the problem with me until we finally figured it out. I had
      unknowingly used a SQL keyword, and it needed to be escaped with
      square brackets. I never would have figured that out on my own.
    </p>

    <p>
      That wasn't the last time I leaned on him, either. Over the years, he
      helped answer more than a few of my ASP.NET questions and was always
      willing to help me think through a problem.
    </p>

    <p>
      By the time I was working at Meisel, Damon and I had known each other
      for several years. We didn't see each other nearly as often as we had
      in college, but we still kept in touch. So when my phone rang one
      afternoon, I figured he just wanted to get some bean soup at Herrera's.
    </p>

    <p class="not-prose text-sm text-neutral-500 dark:text-neutral-400 italic mt-8">
      The rest of the GimmalSoft years are still being written.
    </p>
